Hey, fellow writefag! *Steve_buschemi_skateboard.webm*

While I'm very much not a fan of rape or rape fantasy, It sounds like you might actually have something you can work with, even if it was massively draining to write (and especially if you hate the characters involved).

Let me start by saying that I'm not trying to steer your story for you, nor do I pretend to know your relationship with the piece, but if you're still interested in finishing it (or expanding it into something larger) I'd be happy to offer some ideas.

If you hate all the characters involved so far and you're looking for a protag, you could always set the story up a bit like an early Tarantino flick where the victim is a false protagonist. You can kick off the story with the rape scene - or the lead up to it, at which point it becomes the 'Call to Adventure' or the 'Crossing of the threshold (to use a hero's Journey terms). Then, you could really play on the fallout from the rape as the backdrop for the story. Friends and family who don't know how to deal with the victim can be antagonists, foils, or various other archetypes that all play off the victim's pain or actions driven by it.

As to the actual protag? I'd think that either a love interest or a sibling would be the natural picks (younger sister would make it a horror story of a feels trip). Then, you could focus the growth arc around the protag coming to grips with the new person the victim has become.

From there, it could be a story of triumph (victim pulled back from the brink), a bittersweet story of growth (protag eventually leaves the victim, but not before having some significant trauma and personal growth), or it could be a full-on tragedy, with the protag's life destroyed by the victim (can you say becoming the victimizer?)

Either way, just something to think on...
